          "body": "Verse 24 is a cold pivot. The mercy of the feast has produced temporary peace (6:23), but now Ben-hadad mobilizes his entire army. The resulting siege of Samaria produces the chapter's most harrowing scene. Famine prices have become obscene — a donkey's head at eighty shekels, a fraction of a cab of dove's dung at five shekels (6:25). The numbers are not merely economic; they are covenantal. Deuteronomy 28:52-57 predicted precisely this: siege so severe that the people would eat their own children. When the woman cries to the king for justice and unfolds her story — she and another woman agreed to boil and eat their sons, and now the second woman has hidden her son (6:28-29) — the narrator is recording Deuteronomy 28:53 word for terrible word. This is not random historical tragedy. It is covenant curse arriving on schedule. The king tears his robes, and the people see what he has been concealing beneath them: sackcloth against his body (6:30). He has been performing private grief while exercising public power. The sackcloth is significant — it is the dress of repentance. But in this king, it produces not repentance toward God but fury toward Elisha."
