        "excerpt": "Do not fear, for those who are with us are more than those who are with them. Then Elisha prayed and said, 'O Lord, I pray, open his eyes that he may see.'",
        "body": "The Dothan episode is the chapter's theological center and one of the most luminous passages in the entire Elisha cycle. Its structure is a three-act movement: fear (6:15), reassurance (6:16), confirmation (6:17). The servant's fear is epistemically appropriate given his available data — a great army surrounds the city. Elisha's response does not correct the servant's perception of the threat; it expands his perceptual field. 'Those who are with us are more' is a numerical claim about invisible military reality.\n\nThe prayer for opened eyes (6:17) is not a prayer for new information but for new perception of existing reality. The heavenly host was already there. The mountain was already full of horses and chariots of fire. The servant's opened eyes confirm what Elisha already saw by faith. This is the passage's most enduring pastoral claim: the protective presence of the LORD is not contingent on human perception of it. Calvin notes on this passage that God's servants are never truly unprotected, only unable to see their protection. The opened eyes are the grace that makes the invisible visible — a gift available by prayer.\n\nThe blindness of the Aramean army (6:18) and its mirror restoration (6:20) complete the chapter's sight-theology. The same LORD who opens spiritual eyes closes physical ones. Both actions are in response to Elisha's brief prayer — two sentences that accomplish what entire armies cannot. The Hebrew word for the blindness imposed on the Arameans (*sanverim*) appears elsewhere only in Genesis 19:11, where the men of Sodom are struck blind at Lot's door. The allusion is pointed: the same divine power that protected Lot's household from violent men in Sodom protects Elisha's community at Dothan. Reformed and classical Arminian interpreters agree that this passage teaches sovereign divine protection of His servants; where they differ is in the mechanism and universal applicability of such protection — whether it promises physical deliverance for all believers or specifically authenticates the prophetic office.\n\nThe feast that resolves the military encounter (6:22-23) is theologically unexpected and narratively satisfying. Elisha's instruction — 'set bread and water before them, that they may eat and drink and go to their master' (6:22) — overrides both the king's vengeful instinct and conventional military logic. The result recorded in verse 23 is precise: 'the marauding bands of Arameans did not come again into the land of Israel.' Mercy achieves military peace. This is not naive diplomacy; it is the outworking of the same divine sovereignty that deployed the heavenly army. The LORD has decided the outcome; Elisha mediates it through mercy rather than violence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sanverim* (blindness, 6:18) — a rare word, possibly related to a root meaning 'dazzlement' or 'struck blind by light' rather than mere darkness. Its only other OT occurrence is Genesis 19:11. *Paqach* (to open eyes, 6:17, 20) is used in Isaiah 35:5 of eschatological eye-opening — 'the eyes of the blind shall be opened.' The Elisha cycle participates in that prophetic vocabulary: Elisha's ministry as a foretaste of ultimate divine deliverance."
