        "excerpt": "There was a great famine in Samaria; and behold, they besieged it, until a donkey's head was sold for eighty shekels of silver.",
        "body": "The pivot of 6:24 is one of the narrative's sharpest turns. The chapter has demonstrated the LORD's protection, His prophetic intelligence, and His mercy — and now a full siege descends on Samaria. Ben-hadad mobilizes his entire army (not the raiding parties of 6:23 but his full *machaneh*, his assembled force). The resulting famine is measured in prices that signal covenantal horror: a donkey's head — an unclean animal, Levitically forbidden (Leviticus 11:7) — at eighty silver shekels; a quarter-cab of dove's dung at five shekels.\n\nThe economic detail is interpretively crucial. In normal times, eighty shekels was roughly the value of a slave (Exodus 21:32). The price of a donkey's head consuming that sum, and unclean food becoming currency, signals complete economic and covenantal inversion. Deuteronomy 28:52-57 is the intertextual anchor: Moses warned that siege would produce famine so severe that Israelites would eat their own children. The historian is not recording a random atrocity. He is recording covenant curse fulfillment.\n\nThe woman's account in 6:28-29 is Deuteronomy 28:53 happening in real time. She and another woman agreed to eat their sons in sequence; she honored her part of the agreement, but the other woman has hidden her son. The grotesque detail of the broken agreement — one party cannibalizing her own child, the other reneging — captures the complete social dissolution that Moses predicted for covenant-breaking Israel. The king tears his robes; the narrator allows the reader to see the sackcloth beneath (6:30). He is wearing the dress of mourning and repentance under his royal garments — private grief concealed from the public. Douglas Moo and other exegetes of prophetic narrative note that concealed repentance in the Old Testament often signals incomplete repentance: the form without the substance. The sackcloth will not produce confession and turning to the LORD; it will produce rage against Elisha.\n\nThe pastoral dimension of this passage is irreducibly hard. The narrator offers no comfort to the mother, no justice for the children. The horror is recorded without softening precisely because the Deuteronomistic historian's argument requires it: covenant disobedience produces covenant curse, and that curse is not metaphorical. The physical and social destruction of God's people in their own land is the consequence of walking away from the LORD who gave them the land."
